======================================================================
PART 9: THE GOLDEN IDENTITY AND TOURNAMENT INTERPRETATION
======================================================================

phi^n = F(n)*phi + F(n-1)

At n=5: phi^5 = 5*phi + 3

Tournament interpretation at x=2:
  Replace phi with the tournament eigenvalue 2:
  2^n = F(n)*2 + F(n-1)

  Check: 2^5 = 32 = 5*2 + 3 = 13? NO!

  The identity phi^n = F(n)*phi + F(n-1) is specific to phi.
  At x=2: 2^n = J(n)*2 + J(n-1) where J(n) = Jacobsthal.

Verification: 2^n = J(n)*2 + 2*J(n-1)
  n= 1: 2^n =      2, J(n)*2 + 2*J(n-1) =      2, match = True
  n= 2: 2^n =      4, J(n)*2 + 2*J(n-1) =      4, match = True
  n= 3: 2^n =      8, J(n)*2 + 2*J(n-1) =      8, match = True
  n= 4: 2^n =     16, J(n)*2 + 2*J(n-1) =     16, match = True
  n= 5: 2^n =     32, J(n)*2 + 2*J(n-1) =     32, match = True
  n= 6: 2^n =     64, J(n)*2 + 2*J(n-1) =     64, match = True
  n= 7: 2^n =    128, J(n)*2 + 2*J(n-1) =    128, match = True
  n= 8: 2^n =    256, J(n)*2 + 2*J(n-1) =    256, match = True
  n= 9: 2^n =    512, J(n)*2 + 2*J(n-1) =    512, match = True
  n=10: 2^n =   1024, J(n)*2 + 2*J(n-1) =   1024, match = True
  n=11: 2^n =   2048, J(n)*2 + 2*J(n-1) =   2048, match = True

Verification: (-1)^n = -J(n) + 2*J(n-1)
  n= 1: (-1)^n =  -1, -J(n) + 2*J(n-1) =  -1, match = True
  n= 2: (-1)^n =   1, -J(n) + 2*J(n-1) =   1, match = True
  n= 3: (-1)^n =  -1, -J(n) + 2*J(n-1) =  -1, match = True
  n= 4: (-1)^n =   1, -J(n) + 2*J(n-1) =   1, match = True
  n= 5: (-1)^n =  -1, -J(n) + 2*J(n-1) =  -1, match = True
  n= 6: (-1)^n =   1, -J(n) + 2*J(n-1) =   1, match = True
  n= 7: (-1)^n =  -1, -J(n) + 2*J(n-1) =  -1, match = True
  n= 8: (-1)^n =   1, -J(n) + 2*J(n-1) =   1, match = True
  n= 9: (-1)^n =  -1, -J(n) + 2*J(n-1) =  -1, match = True
  n=10: (-1)^n =   1, -J(n) + 2*J(n-1) =   1, match = True
  n=11: (-1)^n =  -1, -J(n) + 2*J(n-1) =  -1, match = True

I(C_n, 2) = 2^n + (-1)^n = J(n) + 4*J(n-1)
  n=3: I(C_n,2) = 7, J(n)+4J(n-1) = 7, match = True
  n=4: I(C_n,2) = 17, J(n)+4J(n-1) = 17, match = True
  n=5: I(C_n,2) = 31, J(n)+4J(n-1) = 31, match = True
  n=6: I(C_n,2) = 65, J(n)+4J(n-1) = 65, match = True
  n=7: I(C_n,2) = 127, J(n)+4J(n-1) = 127, match = True
  n=8: I(C_n,2) = 257, J(n)+4J(n-1) = 257, match = True
  n=9: I(C_n,2) = 511, J(n)+4J(n-1) = 511, match = True

--> I(C_n, 2) is the JACOBSTHAL-LUCAS number: JL(n) = 2^n + (-1)^n
    Just as Lucas L(n) = phi^n + (-1/phi)^n relates to Fibonacci,
    JL(n) = 2^n + (-1)^n relates to Jacobsthal J(n).
    The forbidden H=7 = JL(3) = Jacobsthal-Lucas number!

======================================================================
GRAND SYNTHESIS
======================================================================

THE INDEPENDENCE POLYNOMIAL THESIS:

Tournament theory = Fibonacci theory evaluated at fugacity x=2.

DICTIONARY:
  Fibonacci world (x=1)     Tournament world (x=2)
  ---------------------     ---------------------
  F(n) = Fibonacci           J(n) = Jacobsthal
  L(n) = Lucas               JL(n) = 2^n+(-1)^n = I(C_n,2)
  phi = golden ratio         2 = tournament eigenvalue
  -1/phi                     -1
  phi^n = F(n)phi+F(n-1)    2^n = 2J(n)+2J(n-1)
  Pi(m) = Pisano period     Pi_J(m) = Jacobsthal Pisano

COINCIDENCE MAP:
  7 = I(C_3, 2) = JL(3) = FORBIDDEN
  21 = F(8) = J(6) = T(6) = I(P_4,2) = FORBIDDEN
  15 = max_H(5) = T(5) = 2^4-1 = F(5)*F(4) = FIXED POINT
  1729 = max_H(11)/T(10) = TAXICAB NUMBER

STRUCTURAL CONSTANTS:
  phi^5 = 5*phi + 3 encodes the (5,3) pair
  5 = vertices, 3 = cycle length, 15 = 5*3 = max_H(5)
  x=2 is the unique positive integer fugacity with integer eigenvalues
  x=k(k+1) = oblong numbers are ALL integer-eigenvalue fugacities
  Tournament sits at k=1: x=1*2=2

PERIOD-6: Pi_F(4) = 6 but Pi_J(4) DOES NOT EXIST
  The Jacobsthal matrix mod 4 is SINGULAR (det=-2, 2|4).
  So the period-6 structure is FIBONACCI-SPECIFIC.
  Tournaments inherit period-6 only through the Fibonacci bridge.

THE FORBIDDEN MECHANISM:
  H = I(Omega, 2) where Omega = cycle-arc conflict graph.
  7 = JL(3) is forbidden because K_3 cannot be Omega component (THM-201).
  21 = I(P_4, 2) is forbidden because P_4 cannot be Omega (THM-202).
  63 = 7*9 = JL(3)*I(2K_1,2) is forbidden by THM-201 (K_3 factor).
  189 = 7*27 IS achievable (different factorization of Omega).

